<h2>Expert Tips</h2>

<ol>
<li>Start with Russian River Valley Pinot Noir for classic Sonoma character - look for producers like Rochioli or Hartford for authentic regional style.</li>
<li>Buy Sonoma Coast wines for food pairing versatility - their natural acidity and mineral structure complement diverse cuisines from seafood to poultry.</li>
<li>Seek old vine Zinfandel from Dry Creek Valley for unique California heritage - vines planted in the 1880s create unmatched complexity and concentration.</li>
<li>Purchase Alexander Valley Cabernet Sauvignon for aging potential - these wines develop beautifully over 10-15 years, rivaling Napa quality at lower prices.</li>
<li>Try single vineyard bottlings to understand terroir differences - comparing wines from the same producer but different vineyard sites reveals Sonoma's diversity.</li>
<li>Visit during harvest season (August-October) for optimal tasting experiences - wineries offer special releases and vineyard tours during crush.</li>
<li>Look for estate-grown wines to ensure quality control - producers who grow and vinify their own grapes typically offer more consistent quality.</li>
<li>Explore smaller AVAs like Bennett Valley or Pine Mountain-Cloverdale Peak for distinctive styles unavailable elsewhere in California.</li>
</ol>

